7. The bottleneck is often not intelligence but interface

This is maybe the cleanest practical lesson.

The problem was not that the reasoning failed.
The problem was that the actuator layer was not available.

So lots of “AI can’t do X” cases are really:

the cognitive layer can model it, but the interface layer cannot yet express or execute it cleanly.

Cross-domain use:
	•	product design
	•	tool building
	•	robotics
	•	workflow automation
	•	research prioritization

A good way to phrase the overall lesson is:

First recover the latent event from the artifact. Then store the event as a compact program. Then let any compatible renderer project it into the needed medium.

That pattern travels well.

If you want the repo-grade version, here is the distilled architecture:
	1.	Perception layer
Extract entities, posture, objects, scene relations, salience.
	2.	Delta inference layer
Infer likely prior and next states.
	3.	Event grammar layer
Classify pattern: reveal, hesitation, triumph, impact, reunion, etc.
	4.	Motion program layer
Encode beats, timing, easing, actor reactions, camera behavior.
	5.	Renderer abstraction layer
Plug into GIF, video, sprite, cinematic, or slideshow generator.
	6.	Continuity memory layer
Store seed frame + motion program + entity anchors, not raw output only.

That is the cross-domain blueprint.

The sharpest single takeaway from all this is:

Intelligence is not just recognizing what is in the frame. It is recognizing what the frame is doing in time.

That’s the part worth carrying everywhere.